---
/**
 * CLUSTER A - Autoria & Provas
 * Página: /en/creator/case-series-safety/
 * Prioridade: P0
 * Intenção: Prova de segurança + dados concretos
 */
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumb from '@components/ui/Breadcrumb.astro';
import SchemaArticle from '@components/seo/SchemaArticle.astro';

const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
  { name: 'Creator', url: '/creator' },
  { name: 'Case Series Safety', url: '/creator/case-series-safety' },
];

const keywords = [
  'ENDOMIDFACE safety',
  'facial surgery complications',
  'nerve injury prevention',
  'Direct Vision safety record',
  'Dr Robério Brandão cases',
  'facial surgery outcomes',
  'midface lift safety',
];

const safetyData = {
  totalCases: '1,500+',
  permanentNerveInjury: '0',
  yearsExperience: '18+',
  transientWeakness: '<2%',
  hematoma: '<1%',
  revision: '<3%',
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="ENDOMIDFACE® Safety Record | 1,500+ Cases"
  description="Documented safety data from Dr. Robério Brandão's ENDOMIDFACE by Direct Vision case series. Over 1,500 facial surgeries with zero permanent motor nerve injuries. Evidence-based safety analysis."
  keywords={keywords}
>
  <SchemaArticle
    title="1,500+ Cases, Zero Permanent Neural Injury — ENDOMIDFACE® Safety Record"
    description="Comprehensive safety analysis of ENDOMIDFACE by Direct Vision technique based on documented case series"
    section="Clinical Safety"
    keywords={keywords}
    articleType="MedicalWebPage"
  />

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-primary-900">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <Breadcrumb items={breadcrumbs} class="text-primary-300 mb-8" />

      <p class="text-accent-400 text-sm font-semibold tracking-wider uppercase mb-4">
        Documented Safety Record
      </p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-serif text-white mb-6">
        1,500+ Cases, Zero Permanent Neural Injury
      </h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-primary-200">
        The most compelling evidence for any surgical technique is its safety record. Here's what 18
        years of documented outcomes reveal about <strong class="text-white"
          >ENDOMIDFACE® by Direct Vision</strong
        >.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Key Stats Banner -->
  <section class="py-8 bg-accent-500">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-4 gap-6 text-center text-white">
        <div>
          <p class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold">{safetyData.totalCases}</p>
          <p class="text-sm opacity-90">Total Surgeries</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold">{safetyData.permanentNerveInjury}</p>
          <p class="text-sm opacity-90">Permanent Nerve Injuries</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold">{safetyData.yearsExperience}</p>
          <p class="text-sm opacity-90">Years of Data</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold">{safetyData.transientWeakness}</p>
          <p class="text-sm opacity-90">Transient Weakness</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Understanding the Data -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-ivory">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif text-primary-900 mb-8">Understanding This Safety Record</h2>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-warmGray">
        <p class="text-xl">
          When evaluating any surgical technique, safety data matters more than marketing claims.
          Let's examine what these numbers actually mean and how they compare to published
          literature on facial surgery.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif text-primary-900 mt-10 mb-4">
          What "Zero Permanent Neural Injury" Means
        </h3>

        <p>
          In facial surgery, the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII) is the primary concern. This nerve
          controls facial movement — smiling, eye closure, forehead elevation. Injury to this nerve
          can result in:
        </p>

        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <strong>Transient weakness:</strong> Temporary loss of function that resolves within weeks
            to months
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Permanent weakness:</strong> Persistent loss of function that does not fully recover
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p>In Dr. Brandão's case series of over 1,500 ENDOMIDFACE procedures:</p>

        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Permanent motor nerve injuries:</strong> Zero documented cases</li>
          <li><strong>Transient weakness:</strong> Less than 2% of cases, all fully resolved</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-accent-500 p-6 my-8">
          <p class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-2">Important Clarification</p>
          <p class="text-warmGray">
            "Zero" refers to documented <em>permanent</em> motor nerve injury. Transient weakness — temporary
            weakness that resolves completely — does occur in a small percentage of cases, as it does
            with any technique that works near the facial nerve. The distinction is critical: transient
            weakness is a known, expected possibility; permanent injury is what we work to prevent absolutely.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif text-primary-900 mt-10 mb-4">
          Why Direct Vision Enhances Safety
        </h3>

        <p>
          The safety record of ENDOMIDFACE® by Direct Vision isn't accidental. It's built into the
          technique's fundamental design:
        </p>

        <ol class="space-y-4">
          <li>
            <strong>Direct Visualization:</strong> Unlike endoscopic approaches where you view anatomy
            through a camera, Direct Vision means your eyes are directly observing the surgical field.
            There's no camera delay, no parallax distortion, no equipment malfunction risk.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Defined Anatomical Planes:</strong> The technique follows specific anatomical planes
            where critical structures are predictably located. You're not working blind — you know exactly
            where the facial nerve branches should be at each stage.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Tactile Feedback:</strong> Direct surgical approach provides haptic (touch) feedback
            that camera systems cannot. You feel tissue density changes, vessel pulsations, and other
            subtle cues.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>No Equipment Dependency:</strong> Equipment-dependent techniques introduce failure
            points. If an endoscopic tower malfunctions, you're compromised. Direct Vision requires only
            surgical loupes and headlamp — tools with near-zero failure rates.
          </li>
        </ol>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif text-primary-900 mt-10 mb-4">
          Comparison to Published Literature
        </h3>

        <p>
          How does this safety record compare to published complication rates for facial surgery?
          The following ranges come from peer-reviewed literature:
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Comparison Table -->
      <div class="my-8 overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full border-collapse bg-white rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="bg-primary-900 text-white">
              <th class="text-left p-4 font-semibold">Complication</th>
              <th class="text-center p-4 font-semibold">Literature Range</th>
              <th class="text-center p-4 font-semibold">ENDOMIDFACE® (Direct Vision)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100">
            <tr>
              <td class="p-4 font-medium text-primary-900">Permanent Facial Nerve Injury</td>
              <td class="p-4 text-center text-warmGray">0.5% - 2.5%</td>
              <td class="p-4 text-center font-bold text-green-600">0%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50">
              <td class="p-4 font-medium text-primary-900">Transient Facial Weakness</td>
              <td class="p-4 text-center text-warmGray">5% - 15%</td>
              <td class="p-4 text-center font-bold text-green-600">&lt;2%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="p-4 font-medium text-primary-900">Hematoma Requiring Drainage</td>
              <td class="p-4 text-center text-warmGray">2% - 5%</td>
              <td class="p-4 text-center font-bold text-green-600">&lt;1%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50">
              <td class="p-4 font-medium text-primary-900">Revision Surgery Rate</td>
              <td class="p-4 text-center text-warmGray">5% - 10%</td>
              <td class="p-4 text-center font-bold text-green-600">&lt;3%</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-warmGray">
        <p class="text-sm text-softGray italic">
          Note: Literature ranges are approximations from multiple published studies and vary based
          on technique, patient selection, and surgeon experience. Direct comparison is complex due
          to varying definitions and reporting standards. These figures are provided for general
          context, not rigorous meta-analysis.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif text-primary-900 mt-10 mb-4">Patient Selection Matters</h3>

        <p>
          Honest safety reporting requires acknowledging that patient selection affects outcomes.
          Dr. Brandão is clear about the <a
            href="/methods/endomidface/indications"
            class="text-accent-600 hover:text-accent-700 underline">ideal patient profile</a
          > for ENDOMIDFACE®:
        </p>

        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Primary demographic:</strong> Patients aged 45-65 years</li>
          <li>
            <strong>Not ideal for:</strong> Patients over 70 with severe SMAS redundancy (better served
            by traditional deep plane)
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Best results:</strong> Modern Face patients (those with prior filler/bioestimulator
            treatment)
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          Proper case selection isn't about avoiding difficult cases — it's about matching technique
          to patient. A technique that works beautifully for 80% of your patients is valuable
          precisely because you recognize the 20% who need a different approach.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif text-primary-900 mt-10 mb-4">Reproducibility in Training</h3>

        <p>
          A technique's safety must be reproducible when taught to other surgeons. The over <strong
            >130 surgeons trained</strong
          > in ENDOMIDFACE® by Direct Vision have reported similar safety profiles in their own practices,
          suggesting that the technique's safety isn't solely dependent on Dr. Brandão's individual skill
          but is inherent to the methodology itself.
        </p>

        <p>
          This reproducibility is critical. A "safe" technique that only works in the creator's
          hands isn't truly safe — it's personal artistry. ENDOMIDFACE® by Direct Vision is designed
          to be systematically teachable and consistently reproducible.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Disclaimer Section -->
  <section class="py-12 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <div class="p-6 bg-gray-50 border border-gray-200 rounded-xl">
        <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
          <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-2xl text-warmGray">info</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-bold text-primary-900 mb-2">Medical Disclaimer</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-warmGray">
              The safety data presented here is based on Dr. Robério Brandão's documented case
              series and is intended for informational purposes for medical professionals.
              Individual results vary based on patient factors, surgeon experience, and case
              complexity. This information does not constitute medical advice. Surgeons interested
              in learning this technique should pursue proper training. Patients should consult with
              qualified surgeons for individual recommendations.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Related Pages -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-ivory">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-primary-900 mb-6">Related Resources</h2>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <a
          href="/methods/endomidface/complications-prevention"
          class="group block p-6 bg-white rounded-xl hover:shadow-lg transition-all"
        >
          <h3 class="font-bold text-lg text-primary-900 group-hover:text-accent-600 mb-2">
            Complications & Prevention Framework
          </h3>
          <p class="text-warmGray text-sm">
            How potential complications are anticipated and prevented.
          </p>
        </a>
        <a
          href="/methods/endomidface/anatomy-map"
          class="group block p-6 bg-white rounded-xl hover:shadow-lg transition-all"
        >
          <h3 class="font-bold text-lg text-primary-900 group-hover:text-accent-600 mb-2">
            Applied Anatomy Map
          </h3>
          <p class="text-warmGray text-sm">Understanding the anatomical basis for safe surgery.</p>
        </a>
        <a
          href="/creator/timeline"
          class="group block p-6 bg-white rounded-xl hover:shadow-lg transition-all"
        >
          <h3 class="font-bold text-lg text-primary-900 group-hover:text-accent-600 mb-2">
            Development Timeline
          </h3>
          <p class="text-warmGray text-sm">18 years of technique evolution and refinement.</p>
        </a>
        <a
          href="/training"
          class="group block p-6 bg-white rounded-xl hover:shadow-lg transition-all"
        >
          <h3 class="font-bold text-lg text-primary-900 group-hover:text-accent-600 mb-2">
            Training Programs
          </h3>
          <p class="text-warmGray text-sm">Learn the technique directly from Dr. Brandão.</p>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-primary-900">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 text-center">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif text-white mb-4">Safety Through Proper Training</h2>
      <p class="text-xl text-primary-200 mb-8">
        The safety record of ENDOMIDFACE® depends on proper technique. Learn from the source through
        structured mentorship programs.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row justify-center gap-4">
        <a
          href="/training"
          class="inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-2 px-8 py-4 bg-accent-500 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-accent-600 transition-colors font-semibold text-lg"
        >
          Training Programs
        </a>
        <a
          href="/contact"
          class="inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-2 px-8 py-4 border border-white/30 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-white/10 transition-colors text-lg"
        >
          Contact Us
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
